        "Question": "Pedro, believing his house was on his own Lot No. 123 (but mistakenly built on Juan's Lot No. 124), is a builder in good faith. What are the rights given to Juan (the landowner) under the law? Explain. ",
        "Answer": "If Pedro is a builder in good faith, Juan as owner of the land, may appropriate the house built by Pedro but he has to pay indemnity to the latter. Juan may also compel Pedro to buy the land provided that its value is not considerably higher than the house. The law (Article 448, Civil Code) grants to the landowner the right to appropriate the works introduced on the land by a builder in good faith or in the alternative, he may compel the builder or planter to buy the land, if the value thereof is not considerably higher than the building or the trees; he may also ask the sower to pay proper rent."
