        "Question": "Krystal sold a parcel of land to RBP Corporation, a foreign corporation. RBP Corporation subsequently sold the property to Gloria. Krystal sued both for annulment of sale and reconveyance, alleging the initial sale to RBP was void because RBP was a foreign corporation prohibited from acquiring land. Will Krystal’s suit for annulment of sale and reconveyance prosper? Explain your answer. (4%)",
        "Answer": "No, Krystal's suit for annulment of the sale and reconveyance will not prosper **on the assumption that Gloria is a Filipino citizen**. While the Constitution generally prohibits aliens (including foreign corporations) from owning private land, jurisprudence has settled that if a land is invalidly transferred to an alien who subsequently transfers it to a citizen, **the flaw in the original transaction is considered cured** and the title of the transferee is rendered valid (United Church Board of World Ministries vs. Sebastian, 159 SCR A 446; Halili vs. Court of Appeals and Guzman G.R. No. 113539 March 12, 1998)."
