        "Question": "H, married to W, with children X, Y, and Z, executed a holographic will, disinheriting Z on the ground that the latter once filed a civil case against him in order to collect a particular sum of money he previously owed Z. Was the disinheritance of Z proper? Explain. ",
        "Answer": "No, the disinheritance of Z was **not proper**. The cause for his disinheritance is not one of those grounds listed by law as grounds to disinherit a child or descendant (Article 919, Civil Code). The ground for disinheritance related to accusation requires the child to have accused the testator of a crime for which the law prescribes imprisonment for six years or more, and the accusation must have been found groundless. Based on the facts, what Z filed was a mere civil case to collect a debt of H."
