        "Question": "Mr. A leased his warehouse to Mr. B. Later, A granted B a loan, secured by a mortgage on the warehouse, and B executed a promissory note waiving prior demand. Mr. B defaulted on the rentals and loan. May Mr. A validly claim legal compensation? Explain. ",
        "Answer": "Yes, A may validly claim **partial legal compensation** against B with respect to the unpaid rentals and the sum due from B under the promissory note. Legal compensation takes place by operation of law and extinguishes both debts to the concurrent amount when all the requisites are present (Article 1279 & 1290, Civil Code). Here, A and B are mutual creditor and debtor; both debts consist of money; both debts are due, liquidated and demandable; and there is no retention or controversy commenced by third persons."
