        "Question": "Three siblings, who were co-owners of a property, sold their undivided shares to a retail conglomerate. When the conglomerate demanded partition, the fourth sibling objected. Should the court allow the partition? Explain briefly.",
        "Answer": "Yes, the court should allow the partition of the property. As a rule, no co-owner shall be obliged to remain in the co-ownership, and each co-owner may demand the partition of the thing owned in common at any time, insofar as their share is concerned (Art. 494, CC). The retail conglomerate, having bought the undivided shares of the three siblings, stepped into the shoes of the latter and may therefore ask for partition of the property."
