        "Question": "By clicking on “Agree”, will there be a “meeting of the minds between the user and the app provider enabling access to the user’s contact list, emails, and browsing history, when the terms and conditions allowing such access were not explicitly shown to the user? Explain briefly.",
        "Answer": "No, there will be no meeting of the minds between the app provider and the user even if the latter clicked the “Agree” button. A contract requires consent, which is manifested by the meeting of the offer and acceptance upon the thing and the cause (Art. 1305, 1318, CC). There could have been no ** valid consent** on the part of the user to terms and conditions that are not even made known by the app provider. The consent given by the user pertains only to the use of the app and not specifically to the provider gaining access to personal data like contact lists, emails, and browsing history."
